            <div>
                <h3 style="text-align: center;"><b> CENMIG – Pornchai Matangkasombut Center for Microbial Genomics </b></h3>
                <p>
                    &emsp;&emsp;&emsp;With the rapid advancement of sequencing technology, <b>whole genome sequencing (WGS)</b> is now becoming a standard laboratory technique in microbiology. The cost of WGS is now less than 50 USD per
                    genome, cheaper than multi-locus sequencing while giving much more information. It is thus expected that WGS will soon find its ways to a wider arena of applied microbiological research and eventually medical services.
                    Its current potentials include identification of drug resistance genes, identification of disease outbreaks, pathogen surveillance, and many more.
                </p>
                <p>
                    &emsp;&emsp;&emsp;<b>Pornchai Matangkasombut Center for Microbial Genomics – CENMIG</b> – was established in 2020, and is currently managed by the Department of Microbiology, Faculty of Science, Mahidol University. The
                    center was founded by a group of ambitious researchers with various expertise, including microbiologists, immunologists, evolutionary biologists, epidemiologists, clinicians, bioinformaticians, and statisticians, aiming
                    to study important pathogens and infectious diseases that are particularly prevalent among ASEAN populations. The main goal is to accelerate the use of WGS technology in diagnosis, prevention, and treatment of infectious
                    diseases, as well as bettering public health disease control policy through better understanding of pathogenesis, evolution, and epidemiology of pathogens. The core activities of the center are to analyse WGS data, and
                    interpret the results, as well as to provide bioinformatician capacity building for Thailand and ASEAN. The main topics of research include the study of pathogen genomes, pathogen discovery and identification through the
                    use of metagenomic approaches, and phylogenetic analysis of pathogens.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div style="background-color: #ededed;">
